\begin_layout Standard
The goal of the axes scene is to show how the system of rest coordinates
 for a moving particle are mapped into the rest frame of other particles
 - here, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

world frame
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 - in which the first particle as moving.
 The basis vectors for the world frame are labeled 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y,ct)$
\end_inset

; and those for the moving particle are labeled 
\begin_inset Formula $(x',y',ct')$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $ct'$
\end_inset

 represents the particle's 3-velocity here through the (2+1) Minkowski space,
 analogous to the 4-velocity in real-world 4D spacetime.
 The point is that 
\begin_inset Formula $ct'$
\end_inset

 is always tangent to the particle's path, and shows where the particle
 will be if it keeps its current velocity.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $ct'$
\end_inset

 is notable because in SR, it is not generally perpendicular to the 
\begin_inset Formula $x'y'$
\end_inset

plane in all frames of reference.
 That is, space and time between different frames are mixed - motion along
 only along time (parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $ct'$
\end_inset

) for the moving particle in frame 
\begin_inset Formula $S'$
\end_inset

 has a changing spatial component in frame 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 (along 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the above picture).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any frame 
\begin_inset Formula $S'$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $x'y'$
\end_inset

 plane gives the surface of simultaneity; events in this plane are simultaneous
 for observers within the frame.
 The phenomena of relativity of simultaneity refers to the fact that given
 events A, B, and C such that A and B are simultaneous in frame S, and B
 and C are simultaneous frame 
\begin_inset Formula $S'$
\end_inset

, events A and C will generally not be simultaneous in either frame S or
 
\begin_inset Formula $S'$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

